The s-s-h server.

So far we have looked at the client side. On the server side, a daemon called s-s-h-d listens on port twenty-two and handles incoming connections, and its behaviour is controlled by a configuration file in the s-s-h directory under slash e-t-c, possibly extended by drop-in files alongside it.

A handful of settings are the ones you will actually touch. The port setting changes which port it listens on. The permit-root-login setting controls whether the root user may log in over s-s-h; a sensible value forbids password logins for root, or you may disable root s-s-h entirely and do administration through sudo from a regular account. The password-authentication setting, turned off, refuses all password attempts and requires keys, which is the single biggest hardening win. You can also restrict access to named users or a named group, cap the number of failed attempts before disconnecting, and send keepalives to detect dead clients.

There is one workflow you must internalise, because getting it wrong locks you out. After editing the configuration, always test and reload before you disconnect. Running s-s-h-d with the dash t flag checks the syntax, staying silent if all is well and printing errors if not. Then reloading the service applies the changes while leaving existing sessions alive. The crucial drill is this: keep your current session open, open a second, fresh session and confirm it works, and only then close the first. That way, if a mistake breaks new logins, you still have a way back in to fix it. As a hardening checklist for production, the essentials are: disable password authentication, disable or restrict root login, use a firewall to limit who can even reach the port, and watch the authentication log for repeated failures.
